ce:section.ce:para:
The binding of SiPc-NH2 to CuCl2 was also verified by Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR), X-ray-photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) and Mass spectra. In FT-IR, the characteristic peak for –NH2 of SiPc-NH2 appeared at lower frequency of ∼ 2846 cm−1 due to the electron shielding effect of the macrocyclic ring of Pc towards the axial ligands. In contrast, the –NH2 peak for SiPc-NH2-CuCl2 shifted back to higher frequency of ∼ 2927 cm−1 attributed to the reduced electron density after binding with Cu2+; The 1:1 complex was also confirmed by mass peak at m/z 906.3150 assigned to the m/z peak of {[SiPc-NH2-CuCl2] + Na+}+ comparing to the calculated m/z 906.3142 (Fig. 9
                        ). In XPS spectra, two extra peaks come from Cu 2p and Cl 2p photoelectrons appeared in the spectrum of SiPc-NH2-CuCl2 comparing to that of SiPc-NH2, which clearly reveals the coexistent of Cu2+ and Cl- in the binding complex (Fig. 9b). The core-level high-resolution electron spectra of C 1 s, N 1 s and O1s from either SiPc-NH2 or SiPc-NH2-CuCl2 were also analyzed and compared. The changes of XPS peak pattern, in particular for O1s, obviously manifested photoelectron variations after Cu2+ binding around atoms of C, N and O (Fig. 10
                        ). All these results systematic disclose the 1:1 chelate of CuCl2/SiPc-NH2.
